  "prompt": "What are the comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different nations?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different jurisdictions:\n\n1. United States\n- Comprehensive legal framework under Bank Secrecy Act\n- Strict reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Aggressive criminal prosecution\n- Focus on international cooperation\n\n2. European Union\n- Unified Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Risk-based approach\n- Enhanced customer due diligence\n- Centralized beneficial ownership registries\n\n3. United Kingdom\n- Proceeds of Crime Act\n- Sophisticated financial intelligence unit\n- Strong regulatory compliance mechanisms\n- Emphasis on professional sector accountability\n\n4. Switzerland\n- Historically more permissive legal environment\n- Recent reforms increasing transparency\n- Strong banking secrecy traditions\n- Increasing international cooperation\n\n5. China\n- Centralized regulatory approach\n- Strict criminal penalties\n- State-controlled financial monitoring\n- Limited transparency in enforcement\n\n6. Russia\n- Developing legal framework\n- Inconsistent enforcement\n- Higher tolerance for complex financial schemes\n- Limited international cooperation\n\n7. Singapore\n- Stringent regulatory environment\n- Advanced technological monitoring\n- Severe criminal penalties\n- Strong international collaboration\n\nThese approaches reflect varying legal, cultural, and economic contexts, with increasing global convergence toward stricter anti-money laundering standards.",
